   Alexander  . Compare   Saunders  .","German: topographic name for someone who lived on sandy soil, from   Sand   1 + <i>-er</i>, suffix denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":18,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Saunders was born about 1437, in Surrey, England, his father, William Saunders, was 28 and his mother, Joan Carew, was 18. He had at least 2 sons with Alice Olney. He died in 1478, in Banbury, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 42, and was buried in Banbury, Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"about 1437–1478":"umbes 1437–1478","1437–1478":"1437–1478","1448–1480":"1448–1480","1455–1518":"1455–1518","1456–1518":"1456–1518","–Female":"Surnud","1450–1494":"1450–1494","–1511":"–1511","141